Data Description

The data I choose describes housing prices along with some details about the home. I am interested in looking modeling the sale price based on the year built, lot size, living square feet, size of basement, and garage size.

data <- read.csv("train_house.csv") %>%
  dplyr::select(SalePrice, YearBuilt, LotArea, GrLivArea, TotalBsmtSF, GarageArea)

  

#Some data cleaning to make it easier look at individually
salePrice <- split.data.frame(data['SalePrice'], data$SalePrice)
yearBuilt <- split.data.frame(data['YearBuilt'], data$YearBuilt)
lotArea <- split.data.frame(data['LotArea'], data$LotArea)
livingArea <- split.data.frame(data['GrLivArea'], data$GrLivArea)
basementSize <- split.data.frame(data['TotalBsmtSF'], data$TotalBsmtSF)
baths <- split.data.frame(data['GarageArea'], data$GarageArea)

salePrice_summ <- data %>%
  summarise(mean = mean(SalePrice), sd = sd(SalePrice), median = median(SalePrice),   IQR = IQR(SalePrice), mode = getmode(SalePrice), sampeSize = length(SalePrice))
yearBuilt_summ <- data %>%
  summarise(mean = mean(YearBuilt), sd = sd(YearBuilt), median = median(YearBuilt),   IQR = IQR(YearBuilt), mode = getmode(YearBuilt), sampeSize = length(YearBuilt))
lotArea_summ <- data %>%
  summarise(mean = mean(LotArea), sd = sd(LotArea), median = median(LotArea),   IQR = IQR(LotArea), mode = getmode(LotArea), sampeSize = length(LotArea))
livingArea_summ <- data %>%
  summarise(mean = mean(GrLivArea), sd = sd(GrLivArea), median = median(GrLivArea),   IQR = IQR(GrLivArea), mode = getmode(GrLivArea), sampeSize = length(GrLivArea))
basementSize_summ <- data %>%
  summarise(mean = mean(TotalBsmtSF), sd = sd(TotalBsmtSF), median = median(TotalBsmtSF),   IQR = IQR(TotalBsmtSF), mode = getmode(TotalBsmtSF), sampeSize = length(TotalBsmtSF))
GarageArea_summ <- data %>%
  summarise(mean = mean(GarageArea), sd = sd(GarageArea), median = median(GarageArea),   IQR = IQR(GarageArea), mode = getmode(GarageArea), sampeSize = length(GarageArea))


cols <- c('Sale Price', 'Year Built', 'Lot Size', 'Living Square Ft', 'Basement Square Ft', 'Garage Size')

Regression Model

model <- lm(SalePrice ~ YearBuilt+LotArea+GrLivArea+TotalBsmtSF+GarageArea, data=data)
coef <- coefficients(model)
anova <- anova(model)
summary <- summary(model)
ci <- as_tibble(confint(model, level=0.95))
t <- as_tibble(summary[[4]])
#Adding a variable column to table
Variable <- c('Intercept', 'Year Built', 'Lot Size', 'Living Square Ft', 'Basement Square Ft', 'Garage Area')
col.Variable2 <- data.frame(Variable)
summ3 <- cbind2(col.Variable2, t)
knitr::kable(summ3, align='lccrr')

Confidence Interval for \(\beta_i\)

The confidence interval for year built is (628.54, 798.54).

The confidence interval for lot size is (0.2, 0.66).

The confidence interval for living square feet is (66.48, 76.46).

The confidence interval for basement square feet is (29.56, 41.96).

The confidence interval for garage area is (48.38, 74.91).

Testing for Significance of Regression Line

Hypotheses

\(H_0: \ \beta_1 = \beta_2 = \beta_3 = \beta_4 = \beta_5 = 0\)
\(H_1: \ \mbox{at least one } \beta_i \ne 0\)

Test Statistic

\(F_0 = 732.22\).

p-value

\(p < 0.0001\).

Rejection Region

Reject if \(p < \alpha\), where \(\alpha=0.05\).

Conclusion and Interpretation

Reject \(H_0\). There is sufficient evidence to suggest that the regression line is significant.

Adjusted \(R^2\)

\(R_{adj}^2=0.71\); that is, approximately 71% of the variance in home sale price is explained by the current model (Year Built, Lot Size, Living Square Ft, Basement Square Ft, and Garage Size).

Model Assumptions

Lets verify that the residuals have a normal distribution with a mean of zero and a constant variance.

res <- data.frame(summary$residuals)
ggplot(data=res, aes(x=res$summary.residuals)) +
    geom_density(alpha=.3, fill='red') +
    theme_ipsum() +
    xlab('Residuals') + 
    ylab('Density')

ggplot(data=data, aes(x=model$fitted.values, y=res$summary.residuals)) +
    geom_point(alpha=.5) +
    theme_ipsum() +
    xlab('Fitted Values') + 
    ylab('Redisual')

The residual distribution is approximately normal with a mean of zero. However, the variance does not appear to be constant. This means that the predictions might not be trustworthy. The variance plot shows that the error is much higher and not consistent for higher sales prices, notice the cone like shape.

The above plots above show the relationship each predictor has with the outcome variable. This is done by holding the other variables constant and having them equal their coefficient. Some of the plots are log-like, clustered, or linear-like. This can be a sign that the relationship is not linear, which could help explain the variance assumption be violated. Some plots may look more linear is the extreme values did not exist. Such as the lot size one, if lot sizes larger than 20,000 square feet were not included is may look more linear than a cluster with some outliers.

#Plot fitted values vs known values.
get_err <- lm(model$fitted.values ~ data$SalePrice)

ggplot(data=data, aes(x=data$SalePrice, y=model$fitted.values, color=get_err$residuals)) +
    geom_jitter(alpha=.5) +
    geom_abline(intercept = 0, slope = 1) +
    theme_ipsum() +
    xlab('Known Values') + 
    ylab('Fitted Values') +
    scale_color_gradient(low = "yellow", high = "blue", na.value = NA) + 
    guides(color=guide_legend(title="Error"))

I wanted a way to look at the accuracy of the model. So I used the known values to model the predicted values and get the error. Theoretically, if the model is 100% accurate the scatter plot should mimic y=x. The further away a dot is from the line, the higher the error.
